the sky fades and the rocket is in a small boy's hand. he is running on the sidewalk, one hand holding his mother's hand and the other holding the toy rocket. he is wearing a space helmet  he lets go of his mother's hand, runs around her, and then flies the rocket over a fire hydrant. he is wearing a cardboard jetpack with streamers flying behind him and a shirt with a space patch. 

 the boy looks behind him,stops,  lets go of his mother's hand, and walks backwards. 

we see from the boy's eyes. he lifts thehelmet covering his face. he sees a rocket ride. the boy's eyes get wide and he grins . 

we see a sign next to the ride that says 5 cents. the words coin operated are shown on the screen. the boy's mother takes his hand and tries to walk away. they boy takes his hand away and looks up at his mother. he excitedly takes a coin out of his pocket and puts it in the machine. he runs around and gets in the rocket, falling into it. he sits up and closes his helmet. his mother salutses him and he salutes back. he presses a button on the ride and looks up at the sky. 

we see the sky in front of the boy. he looks up expectantly. the rocket starts moving up and down very slowly. the boy's expression looks sad and disappointed. he looks to either side of him and hits the rocket ride. he presses the button again repeatedly.  the ride stops. the boy looks very sad. he lifts up the face covering of his helmet, takes the helmet off, and looks up sadly at the sky. he sighs. he looks into the distance and smiles. he stands up, sticking his tongue out in concentration and putting his hand in his pocket. he takes it out of his pocket and sits down. he looks around him and sees a sign that says lemons. he smiles and gets out of the rocket ride. 

we see the boy pulling a box on the sidewalk. he uses a hammer and nails and paints some wood, building a lemonade stand. he cuts and juices lemons and hands a cup of lemonade to someone. he gets money. the boy is standing at the lemonade stand, looking around happily. 

the boy continues to stand in his lemonade stand, with customers coming and going. we see the boy age and turn into a teenager, an adult, and finally into an elderly man with white hair and a long white beard. the man smiles and sighs and looks at a large bag of money next to his lemonade stand that he has earned. he hangs up a sign on the lemonade stand that says "closed." the man puts the large bag of money in a wagon and walks across a crosswalk, pulling the wagon behind him. he looks up, smiling and eyes wide. we see the same rocket ride that he rode when he was a child. he squints his eyes, picks up the bag of money, and starts pouring it into the ride. he drops the empty bag, walks up to the rocket, and gets into it. he smiles and puts his space helmet on, pulling down the face cover. he closes his eyes and presses the button on the ride. nothing happens, and the man looks down sadly. he presses the button again repeatedly. 

he shakes his head and hits the ride, causing two coins that were stuck to fall into the machine. the man looks to either side of him as the ride slowly starts to move. his eyes get big and he looks up at the sky. the rocket flies away off of the ride, and we see the man in the rocket flying through the clouds. 

the mechanical part of the rocket ride continues to move, and there are black sreaks on the ground ad the wall from whe nthe rocket took off.

A small rocket appears against a cloudy sky. It weaves in and out of the clouds, swaying from side to side.
The background changes to a street where the rocket imitates a flying motion in the hand of a small boy. He wears an astronaut helmet and a jetpack.
He runs in circles beside and around a woman in pink.
The boy wears a T-shirt with a word on the front 'space'.
As he walks along, he suddenly stops, turns around and stares wide-eyed.
Across from him is a coin-operated rocket ride.
The boy remains frozen, his eyes fixed on the ride. He blinks and a smile appears on his face. As his smile widens, he bounces up and down and turns his head to face the woman. He turns back, still jumping, until he notices a sign beside the ride. It reads '5 cents.'
The words 'Coin Operated' appear on the screen.
The woman appears from the boy's left and walks to his side. She grabs him by the hand and attempts to drag him away, but he resists and pulls away. He clasps his hands together and looks up at her. He stops, pulls a coin from his pocket, and runs to the coin slot. He pushes the coin in, frowns, slaps the machine, smiles, and runs to the ride. He climbs in and seats himself. He pulls his helmet down. The woman salutes. The boy salutes. He presses a big yellow button inside the rocket and it begins to rock. He looks up at the sky at the moon, white against the blue sky. The ride tips back and forth and his eyes remain fixed on the moon. He blinks, then glances from side to side. His smile disappears, and he turns and hits the back of the ride with his fist a couple of times. It continues to rock, and he presses buttons on the dashboard. The ride continues to rock. It comes to a stop, at which the boy frowns and turns to look at the ground. He takes off his helmet. He looks up at the moon. A smile flashes temporarily across the boy's face and he stands up in the ride. He stretches his whole body upward, holding out his tongue, then looks down. He sits down again, his mouth turned down into a frown. A faint smile reappears as he glances up at the moon again. He climbs out of the ride. Now he drags a box across the pavement. He hammers a nail into a board. He paints another board with up and down strokes. The screen jumps forward to a completed lemonade stand on which he paints a lemon as a planet with a ring and a few yellow stars. He slices a lemon and squeezes it. The boy hands someone a cup and they give him a couple of coins. The boy hands someone else a cup and receives two more coins. He continues to sit at his stand with a banner that says 'lemonade' on the front. A card of lemons sits to the boy's side. He looks from side to side, and the time elapses quickly as the level of lemonade in the jug goes does and the lemons disappear. Customers come and go as his lemons and jug of lemonade refill and disappear again and again. The boy grows bigger as he continues to sell lemonade. His hairstyle gradually changes, and facial hair appears. His hair and beard grow white as he continues to sit at the lemonade stand. His beard grows fuller as he loses most of the hair on top of his head. He closes his eyes and smiles as the quick time elapse slows to a normal pace again. The man looks to his side where there sits a large bag labeled with a dollar sign. He nods and rises from his seat. He hangs a sign that reads 'sorry we're closed.' The sign swings side to side. The man crosses the street pulling the large bag in a small blue wheelbarrow. He bends forward under its weight, taking slow steps forward. He stops to look at the  coin operated ride, still in the same place. He smiles. He turns to lift the bag from the wheelbarrow. He pours the money from the bag into the coin slot on the machine. He watches, holding the empty bag in one hand, then dropping the bag onto the concrete. He takes a few steps forward, places a hand on the ride, and climbs in. He seats himself and puts on his astronaut helmet. He pulls down the visor on the helmet and closes his eyes. He opens his eyes and finds the yellow button on the dashboard. He hesitates and squeezes his eyes shut for a moment, then opens them and presses the button. He stares up at the sky, but the rocket ride doesn't move. He looks down. He shakes his head and lets his fist fall. A couple more coins finish rolling into the coin slot on the machine. The ride begins to move. The wheelbarrow on the pavement begins to shake as well. The rocket ride tilts upward, detaches from the base, and shoots upwards towards the moon, leaving a tail of smoke. As the rocket shoots through the clouds, the face in the astronaut helmet is that of the boy. The screen goes black and credits appear.
The base from the rocket ride remains on the sidewalk. The pins that attached to the ride are still moving against a burnt building backdrop.
The screen switches to a logo and words: Empowered by Nimble Creative. A rocket flies past the logo.

result.title: Coin Operated - Animated Short Film
result.description:
Written & Directed by Nicholas Arioli

"Coin Operated" is an award-winning 5 minute animated short film that spans 70 years in the life of one naive explorer. This film was proudly made by independent artists. 

Facebook - https://www.facebook.com/CoinOperatedFilm
Contact - twoghostsfilms@gmail.com

Official Selection: AFI Fest 2017, TIFF Kids 2018, Hamptons Film Fest 2017, San Francisco Film Fest 2018, Mill Valley Film Fest 2018
Winner, Best Short Animation: Rhode Island Intl Film Fest 2017, Pittsburgh Film Fest 2017, At&T Film Awards 2017
Winner, Audience Award: Palm Springs Intl Short Fest 2017, Naples Intl Film Fest 2017, Brooklyn Film Fest 2017
